nd on the magnitudes of the charges, currents, or magnetic strengths involved and on the distances between the interacting objects.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471258',0),(414,'','Gravitational forces are always attractive. There is a gravitational force between any two masses, but it is very small except when one or both of the objects have large mass—e.g., Earth and the sun.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471259',0),(415,'','Forces that act at a distance (electric, magnetic, and gravitational) can be explained by fields that extend through space and can be mapped by their effect on a test object (a charged object, or a ball, respectively).','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471260',0),(416,'','Newton\'s law of universal gravitation and Coulomb\'s law provide the mathematical models to describe and predict the effects of gravitational and electrostatic forces between distant objects.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471713',0),(417,'','Forces at a distance are explained by fields (gravitational, electric, and magnetic) permeating space that can transfer energy through space. Magnets or electric currents cause magnetic fields; electric charges or changing magnetic fields cause electric f','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471714',0),(418,'','Attraction and repulsion between electric charges at the atomic scale explain the structure, properties, and transformations of matter, as well as the contact forces between material objects.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471715',0),(419,'','The faster a given object is moving, the more energy it possesses.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470927',0),(420,'','Energy can be moved from place to place by moving objects or through sound, light, or electric currents.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470928',0),(421,'','The term \"heat\" as used in everyday language refers both to thermal energy (the motion of atoms or molecules within a substance) and the transfer of that thermal energy from one object to another. In science, heat is used only for this second meaning; it ','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471215',0),(422,'','The temperature of a system is proportional to the average internal kinetic energy and potential energy per atom or molecule (whichever is the appropriate building block for the system\'s material). The details of that relationship depend on the type of at','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471216',0),(423,'','Motion energy is properly called kinetic energy; it is proportional to the mass of the moving object and grows with the square of its speed.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471294',0),(424,'','A system of objects may also contain stored (potential) energy, depending on their relative positions.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471295',0),(425,'','Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of particles of matter. The relationship between the temperature and the total energy of a system depends on the types, states, and amounts of matter present.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471296',0),(426,'','…and \"electrical energy\" may mean energy stored in a battery or energy transmitted by electric currents.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471716',0),(427,'','Energy is a quantitative property of a system that depends on the motion and interactions of matter and radiation within that system. That there is a single quantity called energy is due to the fact that a system\'s total energy is conserved, even as, with','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471748',0),(428,'','At the macroscopic scale, energy manifests itself in multiple ways, such as in motion, sound, light, and thermal energy.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471749',0),(429,'','These relationships are better understood at the microscopic scale, at which all of the different manifestations of energy can be modeled as a combination of energy associated with the motion of particles and energy associated with the configuration 