resources/S2471331',0),(469,'','However, because light can travel through space, it cannot be a matter wave, like sound or water waves.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471332',0),(470,'','Electromagnetic radiation (e.g., radio, microwaves, light) can be modeled as a wave of changing electric and magnetic fields or as particles called photons. The wave model is useful for explaining many features of electromagnetic radiation, and the partic','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471797',0),(471,'','When light or longer wavelength electromagnetic radiation is absorbed in matter, it is generally converted into thermal energy (heat). Shorter wavelength electromagnetic radiation (ultraviolet, X-rays, gamma rays) can ionize atoms and cause damage to livi','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471798',0),(472,'','Photoelectric materials emit electrons when they absorb light of a high-enough frequency.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471799',0),(473,'','Atoms of each element emit and absorb characteristic frequencies of light. These characteristics allow identification of the presence of an element, even in microscopic quantities.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2472010',0),(474,'','People also use a variety of devices to communicate (send and receive information) over long distances.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470600',0),(475,'','Digitized information can be transmitted over long distances without significant degradation. High-tech devices, such as computers or cell phones, can receive and decode information—convert it from digitized form to voice—and vice versa.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470961',0),(476,'','Digitized signals (sent as wave pulses) are a more reliable way to encode and transmit information.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471333',0),(477,'','Multiple technologies based on the understanding of waves and their interactions with matter are part of everyday experiences in the modern world (e.g., medical imaging, commu