cules and oxygen molecules are broken and new compounds are forme','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471841',0),(504,'','Animals have body parts that capture and convey different kinds of information needed for growth and survival. Animals respond to these inputs with behaviors that help them survive. Plants also respond to some external inputs.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470621',0),(505,'','Different sense receptors are specialized for particular kinds of information, which may be then processed by the animal\'s brain. Animals are able to use their perceptions and memories to guide their actions.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470982',0),(506,'','Each sense receptor responds to different inputs (electromagnetic, mechanical, chemical), transmitting them as signals that travel along nerve cells to the brain. The signals are then processed in the brain, resulting in immediate behaviors or memories.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471378',0),(507,'','Plants depend on water and light to grow.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470701',0),(508,'','Plants depend on animals for pollination or to move their seeds around.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470702',0),(509,'','The food of almost any kind of animal can be traced back to plants. Organisms are related in food webs in which some animals eat plants for food and other animals eat the animals that eat plants. Some organisms, such as fungi and bacteria, break down dead','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471108',0),(510,'','Organisms, and populations of organisms, are dependent on their environmental interactions both with other living things and with nonliving factors.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471407',0),(511,'','In any ecosystem, organisms and populations with similar requirements for food, water, oxygen, or other resources may compete with each other for limited resources, access to which consequently constrains their growth and reproduction.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471421',0),(512,'','Growth of organisms and population increases are limited by access to resources.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471422',0),(513,'','Similarly, predatory interactions may reduce the number of organisms or eliminate whole populations of organisms. Mutually beneficial interactions, in contrast, may become so interdependent that each organism requires the other for survival. Although the ','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471423',0),(514,'','Ecosystems have carrying capacities, which are limits to the numbers of organisms and populations they can support. These limits result from such factors as the availability of living and nonliving resources and from such challenges such as predation, com','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471880',0),(515,'','Matter cycles between the air and soil and among plants, animals, and microbes as these organisms live and die. Organisms obtain gases, and water, from the environment, and release waste matter (gas, liquid, or solid) back into the environment.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471109',0),(516,'','Food webs are models that demonstrate how matter and energy is transferred between producers, consumers, and decomposers as the three groups interact within an ecosystem. Transfers of matter into and out of the physical environment occur at every level. D','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471408',0),(517,'','Photosynthesis and cellular respiration (including anaerobic processes) provide most of the energy for life processes.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471881',0),(518,'','Plants or algae form the lowest level of the food web. At each link upward in a food web, only a small fraction of the matter consumed at the lower level is transferred upward, to produce growth and release energy in cellular respiration at the higher lev','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471882',0),(519,'','Photosynthesis and cellular respiration are important components of the carbon cycle, in which carbon is exchanged among the biosphere, atmosphere, oceans, and geosphere through chemical, physical, geological, and biological processes.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471883',0),(520,'','When the environment changes in ways that affect a place\'s physical characteristics, temperature, or availability of resources, some organisms survive and reproduce, others move to new locations, yet others move into the transformed environment, and some ','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470865',0),(521,'','Ecosystems are dynamic in nature; their characteristics can vary over time. Disruptions to any physical or biological component of an ecosystem can lead to shifts in all its populations.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471425',0),(522,'','Biodiversity describes the variety of species found in Earth\'s terrestrial and oceanic ecosystems. The completeness or integrity of an ecosystem\'s biodiversity is often used as a measure of its health.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471426',0),(523,'','A complex set of interactions within an ecosystem can keep its numbers and types of organisms relatively constant over long periods of time under stable conditions. If a modest biological or physical disturbance to an ecosystem occurs, it may return to it','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471884',0),(524,'','Moreover, anthropogenic changes (induced by human activity) in the environment—including habitat destruction, pollution, introduction of invasive species, overexploitation, and climate change—can disrupt an ecosystem and threaten the survival of some spec','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471885',0),(525,'','Being part of a group helps animals obtain food, defend themselves, and cope with changes. Groups may serve different functions and vary dramatically in size (Note: Moved from K–2).','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470825',0),(526,'','Group behavior has evolved because membership can increase the chances of survival for individuals and their genetic relatives.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471886',0),(527,'','Young animals are very much, but not exactly like, their parents. Plants also are very much, but not exactly, like their parents.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470636',0),(528,'','Many characteristics of organisms are inherited from their parents.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470839',0),(529,'','Other characteristics result from individuals\' interactions with the environment, which can range from diet to learning. Many characteristics involve both inheritance and environment.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470840',0),(530,'','Genes are located in the chromosomes of cells, with each chromosome pair containing two variants of each of many distinct genes. Each distinct gene chiefly controls the production of specific proteins, which in turn affects the traits of the individual. C','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471453',0),(531,'','Variations of inherited traits between parent and offspring arise from genetic differences that result from the subset of chromosomes (and therefore genes) inherited.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471454',0),(532,'','Each chromosome consists of a single very long DNA molecule, and each gene on the chromosome is a particular segment of that DNA. The instructions for forming species\' characteristics are carried in DNA. All cells in an organism have the same genetic cont','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471919',0),(533,'','Individuals of the same kind of plant or animal are recognizable as similar but can also vary in many ways.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470637',0),(534,'','Different organisms vary in how they look and function because they have different inherited information.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470841',0),(535,'','The environment also affects the traits that an organism develops.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470842',0),(536,'','In sexually reproducing organisms, each parent contributes half of the genes acquired (at random) by the offspring. Individuals have two of each chromosome and hence two alleles of each gene, one acquired from each parent. These versions may be identical ','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471455',0),(537,'','In addition to variations that arise from sexual reproduction, genetic information can be altered because of mutations. Though rare, mutations may result in changes to the structure and function of proteins. Some changes are beneficial, others harmful, an','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471456',0),(538,'','In sexual reproduction, chromosomes can sometimes swap sections during the process of meiosis (cell division), thereby creating new genetic combinations and thus more genetic variation. Although DNA replication is tightly regulated and remarkably accurate','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471920',0),(539,'','Environmental factors also affect expression of traits, and hence affect the probability of occurrences of traits in a population. Thus the variation and distribution of traits observed depends on both genetic and environmental factors.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471921',0),(540,'','Some kinds of plants and animals that once lived on Earth are no longer found anywhere.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470866',0),(541,'','Fossils provide evidence about the types of organisms that lived long ago and also about the nature of their environments.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470867',0),(542,'','The collection of fossils and their placement in chronological order (e.g., through the location of the sedimentary layers in which they are found or through radioactive dating) is known as the fossil record. It documents the existence, diversity, extinct','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471483',0),(543,'','Anatomical similarities and differences between various organisms living today and between them and organisms in the fossil record, enable the reconstruction of evolutionary history and the inference of lines of evolutionary descent.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471484',0),(544,'','Comparison of the embryological development of different species also reveals similarities that show relationships not evident in the fully-formed anatomy.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471485',0),(545,'','Genetic information provides evidence of evolution. DNA sequences vary among species, but there are many overlaps; in fact, the ongoing branching that produces multiple lines of descent can be inferred by comparing the DNA sequences of different organisms','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471954',0),(546,'','Sometimes the differences in characteristics between individuals of the same species provide advantages in surviving, finding mates, and reproducing.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470868',0),(547,'','Natural selection leads to the predominance of certain traits in a population, and the suppression of others.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471486',0),(548,'','In artificial selection, humans have the capacity to influence certain characteristics of organisms by selective breeding. One can choose desired parental traits determined by genes, which are then passed on to offspring.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471487',0),(549,'','Natural selection occurs only if there is both (1) variation in the genetic information between organisms in a population and (2) variation in the expression of that genetic information—that is, trait variation—that leads to differences in performance amo','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471955',0),(550,'','The traits that positively affect survival are more likely to be reproduced, and thus are more common in the population.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2471956',0),(551,'','For any particular environment, some kinds of organisms survive well, some survive less well, and some cannot survive at all.','http://asn.jesandco.org/resources/S2470869',0),(552,'','Adaptation by natural se